Fifth Avenue & Broadway, west side, at West 25th Street (extreme right) and southward on the Awenue. The Worth Monument (of 1857) separates Fifth Avenue (the photographers vantage point) from Broaday. Utilizing the 24th to 25t Street frontage of the latter are the two hotels, the Albemarle and the Hoffman House. In the block below is the Fifth Avenue Hotel (demolished 1908).
About 1903
Brown Bros., photographers

Fifth Avenue, west side, north from 25th Street.
1907.
Brown Brothers, Photographer.

Fifth Avenue, north from 25th Street, showing traffic conditions on this main thoroughfare at an early date. Note the spire of the Marble Collegiate Reformed Church at the top center. The intersecting street seen in the foreground is 26th Street with the Brunswick Bldg. (right) occupying the Avenue frontage between that
and 27th Street.
This photostat is one of a set filed under various Fifth Avenue locations and Police Activities. Similar material appears on page
229 of the Marc 11, 1909 issue.

This building housed Delmonico's until about 1900, when that establishment moved uptown to Fifth Avenue N.E. corner of 44th Street. June 19, 1912.
